  "preFix": {
    "title": "Pasta e fagioli",
    "subtitle": "The Roman pasta and bean soup",
    "excerpt": "Borlotti beans cooked down with pancetta, tomatoes, and rosemary, finished with small pasta stirred into the thick, brothy soup. One of the great Italian one-pot meals. Hearty enough for dinner, ready in 45 minutes with tinned beans.",
    "sourceNotes": "Pasta e fagioli is one of the classic dishes of Roman and central Italian home cooking, documented at least since the Renaissance. This version uses tinned borlotti beans following the modern Italian home-cook approach.",
    "body": {
      "type": "doc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Pasta e fagioli sits at the border between soup and stew: thick enough to eat with a fork, but still poured from a ladle. The ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "borlotti beans",
              "type": "text",
              "marks": [
                {
                  "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                  "attrs": {
                    "termId": "cmprydsjp0000isv48spz4jg1"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " are partially crushed at the end to thicken the broth, and the pasta is cooked directly in the soup so it absorbs the flavour as it softens. Use ditalini, small tubetti, or any small pasta shape. Do not try to make this ahead with the pasta already added ,  the pasta swells and absorbs all the liquid by the next day.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
